  caption: [The committed flat baseline (_flat-sort_) across the size sweep. Gates and proof size are exact; prove and verify times are means over repeats. Three things grow with the instance and two do not: the gate count and prove time climb together, peak memory climbs fastest of all, while the proof size is fixed and the verify time barely moves.],
  table(
    columns: (auto, auto, auto, auto, auto, auto),
    align: (right, right, right, right, right, right),
    table.header([*$n$*], [*gates*], [*prove (s)*], [*verify (ms)*], [*proof (B)*], [*peak (MB)*]),
    [8],    [7\,074],     [0.17],  [9],  [14\,656], [44],
    [256],  [358\,158],   [4.45],  [9],  [14\,656], [517],
    [1000], [1\,733\,830],[25.1],  [12], [14\,656], [2\,451],
    [3000], [6\,224\,830],[91.9],  [15], [14\,656], [9\,736],
    [4000], [8\,298\,830],[114.5], [29], [14\,656], [13\,262],
  ),
) <tab:flat-costs>

The prover's time follows the gate count almost exactly. From $n = 1000$ to $n = 3000$ the circuit grows $3.6$-fold, from $1.73$ to $6.22$ million gates, and the prove time grows $3.7$-fold, from twenty-five seconds to ninety-two; proving is linear in the size of the circuit, as UltraHonk's prover is, so prove time simply inherits the log-linear shape of the gates. A flat instance of a thousand nodes proves in about twenty-five seconds, three thousand in a minute and a half.

Two of the costs do not grow at all, and they are the ones the chapter will lean on later. The proof is $14\,656$ bytes at every size, from eight nodes to four thousand---a fixed length, the succinctness the proof system promises: the verifier downloads the same small proof whatever the instance. Verification is nearly as flat, a handful of milliseconds throughout, nine at the small end and rising only to fifteen at $n = 3000$. This is the $O(1)$ verifier the rest of the chapter measures everything against---flat's single cheap check, the one @sec:stitching-tax says the external hierarchical variants pay $K$-fold to give up and recursion buys back. We pin it here so that the later "$O(K)$ verifier" has a unit: one flat verification is milliseconds, and one flat proof is fifteen kilobytes.

The cost that grows, and the one that finally bites, is memory. Peak prover memory climbs with the circuit at roughly a kilobyte and a half per gate: half a gigabyte at $n = 256$, two and a half at $n = 1000$, nearly ten at $n = 3000$, and thirteen and a third at $n = 4000$. Set that last figure against the machine. The host holds sixteen gigabytes, and at four thousand nodes the prover is already using thirteen of them. There is no room to go much further. A flat instance of five or six thousand nodes does not prove slowly on this machine---it does not prove at all, because the prover cannot fit the circuit in memory. This is the _wall_. It is not a figure of speech but a measured ceiling, the largest flat instance the hardware will carry, and it is the reason everything after this section exists. Every construction the thesis goes on to build is, at bottom, an attempt to get past this one number: to prove a tour too large for a single prover by cutting it into pieces each small enough to fit, with room to spare. The dualism of @sec:dualism already warned that the cutting cannot lower the _total_ work; the wall is why one would cut anyway.

The flat baseline is now fully read---log-linear in its gates, hashing-bound at about $86$ a hash, succinct in proof and verifier, and walled by memory not far past a thousand nodes. One number remains, and it is a cautionary one: a metric the toolchain reports that looks like it measures cost and, read carelessly, does not.

#subsection([What the Opcode Count Hides], label: <sub:flat-acir>)

Alongside the gate count, the toolchain reports a second size: the ACIR opcode count, the number of operations the circuit compiles to _before_ arithmetization. It sits right next to the gate count in the output, it is smaller and tidier, and it is tempting to read as the circuit's true size. It is not the proving cost, and the gap between the two is worth a paragraph, because taking one for the other is the easiest way to draw a false conclusion from a correct measurement.

The trouble is that an opcode is not a gate, and different opcodes become different numbers of gates. Our own data shows it cleanly. By the opcode count, the pairwise mechanism looks _twice_ as expensive as sort: pairwise compiles to about $2 n^2$ opcodes, sort to about $n^2$, a clean two-to-one. By the gate count, the same two mechanisms sit within a seventh of each other, $8.25 n^2$ against $7.25 n^2$. The opcode count says pairwise costs double; the prover says it costs fourteen percent more. Both are right about what they measure. They disagree because the extra opcodes pairwise spends are multiplications---one opcode and one gate apiece---while the $n^2$ opcodes both mechanisms share are public inputs, one opcode but seven-and-a-quarter gates apiece. The opcode count weighs a multiplication and a public input the same; UltraHonk charges the input seven times more.

The hash is the sharpest form of the same effect. A Poseidon2 call is a single blackbox opcode, indivisible in the ACIR, and it expands to the scores of gates @sub:flat-commit measured. So a hashing-bound circuit---which the committed baseline is---carries an opcode count that badly understates its proving cost: a handful of opcodes per Merkle level standing in for the eighty-six gates each level truly costs. Count opcodes and the committed proof looks lean; prove it and the hashing is the entire bill.

The lesson is the plain one: know what a number measures before you trust it. The opcode count is a pre-arithmetization figure, a fair proxy for how large the circuit _description_ is and how long it takes to compile, but not for what it costs to prove. Proving cost lives in the gates, because the gates are what the prover commits to and what its time and its memory scale with. Gates are therefore the currency this chapter reports, and wherever a comparison could turn on the difference we use them and not opcodes.

Honesty adds one qualification, because this section's own central comparison happens _not_ to suffer the distortion. Full against Merkle crosses at the same $n approx 176$ whether it is read in opcodes or in gates, because a public input and a Merkle level happen to expand at nearly the same rate---$7.25$ gates against about $7.8$. That agreement is luck of composition, not a property of the metric, and the pairwise gap on the very same data shows how readily it breaks. The opcode count was right about the crossover here and would have been wrong about the mechanisms, and nothing in the number itself tells you which case you are in. Which is exactly why one reads the gates.

With that caution logged, the baseline is fully in hand: its scaling, its hashing cost, its succinct verifier, its memory wall, and the one number not to trust. Every construction the earlier chapters built was designed against this baseline. The next section is the first to set their _measured_ gates beside the predictions @chap:hierarchical made for them, and to ask whether the analysis and the prover agree.

#section([Gates Against the Predictions], label: <sec:gates-vs-prediction>)

@chap:hierarchical made two quantitative claims about the prover's gates, both reasoned from the shape of the constructions rather than measured: the _dualism_, that decomposition conserves the prover's total work and charges a tax to recombine, and the _fingerprint lever_, that swapping the sort mechanism for the product trades an expensive coverage check for a cheaper one. This section sets both against the measured gate counts. Both survive the test---and the measurement sharpens the second of them, settling a detail that a convenient one-line summary of the lever gets wrong and that @chap:hierarchical was careful not to.

#subsection([The Dualism, Measured], label: <sub:dualism-measured>)

The dualism of @sec:dualism has two halves, and they can be checked separately. The first is that the $K$ segments, taken together, simply redo the flat proof's work---each segment proving its $M = n\/K$ nodes, the $K$ of them summing back to the same $n$ the flat circuit proved. The second is that the glue is pure addition on top of that conserved work, the recombination the segments cannot do for themselves. Measure the segments alone and the first half is almost exact. At $n = 1000$ the $K$ segment circuits, summed, come to within a whisker of the flat gate count: a factor of $1.004$ of it at $K = 2$, $1.006$ at $K = 4$, $1.008$ at $K = 8$ for plain-sort, and tighter still, $1.001$ to $1.005$, for plain-product. The surplus is under a percent, and it is the per-segment scaffolding---the few thousand fixed gates every circuit carries, now paid $K$ times instead of once---not any growth in the real work. The books balance: split a cost proportional to $n$ into $K$ pieces and add the pieces back up, and the sum is $n$ again, with nothing saved and almost nothing lost. There was never a prize to win there, exactly as @sec:dualism argued.

So the whole of the excess over flat is the glue, and adding it back gives the total the dualism predicted: the conserved segment work, plus a tax to stitch it. @fig:dualism reads that total as a percentage of the flat baseline, and its first lesson is the one the dualism insisted on---every curve sits _above_ the hundred-percent line, at every $n$ and every $K$. The hierarchical total never dips beneath the flat one. There is no crossover, no instance size at which decomposing the proof costs fewer gates than proving it whole; the saving decomposition offers was never in the gate count, and the figure shows the floor holding without exception.

#figure(
  image("/assets/figures/04_dualism_total_work.pdf", width: 100%),
  caption: [Total hierarchical gates as a percentage of the flat baseline, by mechanism, for each variant and segment count $K$. The $100%$ line is the conservation floor: every curve sits above it, at every $n$ and $K$, so no decomposition spends fewer total gates than the flat proof. The tax shrinks as $n$ grows (the glue's fixed cost diluting) and rises with $K$ (more pieces to stitch). Committed-sort, in the left panel, is the exception that does not dilute: its $O(n)$ commitment re-fold rides at a roughly constant fraction of the circuit.],
) <fig:dualism>

How large the tax is, and how it moves, is the figure's second lesson, and it tracks the prediction closely. The tax shrinks as $n$ grows and swells as $K$ grows. Plain-sort cut into eight segments costs $8.3%$ over flat at $n = 256$ but only $1.7%$ at $n = 3000$: the glue's fixed costs, paid once per recombination, dilute against a segment workload that climbs with the instance. And more segments mean more to stitch---more boundary edges to prove, a longer coverage check to run---so at any fixed size the tax rises with $K$. The family's worst case is a small instance cut into many pieces, its best a large instance cut into few, and between them the tax is what @sec:dualism promised: a few percent where the sizes matter, and never, at any size, a saving.

One variant refuses to dilute, and @chap:hierarchical predicted which one. Committed-sort sits $7$ to $17%$ above flat and stays there---$12.5%$ at $n = 256$ and still $7.4%$ at $n = 3000$, where the other three have fallen toward a single percent. The cause is the re-fold the earlier chapter named: to open its commitments the committed-sort glue folds all $n$ of its node values a second time, an $O(n)$ cost riding at a roughly fixed fraction of an $O(n log n)$ circuit, so it holds its share rather than thinning. Committed-product, which folds only a handful of scalars per segment, behaves like the plain variants and dilutes to a third of a percent over flat. Among the four, then, committed-sort carries both the heaviest tax and the only one that does not fade with scale---the measured price of committing an _exact_ sort, precisely the asymmetry @chap:hierarchical drew between the two committed variants.

The dualism, then, holds in full and down to the percent: the segments conserve, the glue taxes, the total never falls below flat, and the one variant that should resist dilution does. The chapter's second gate claim, the fingerprint lever, is next---and it is the one the measurement does not merely confirm but sharpens.

#subsection([The Lever, Measured], label: <sub:lever-measured>)

The fingerprint lever swaps the sort mechanism for the product, and @chap:hierarchical traced two effects of the swap on the glue. The first is a shrinking of each segment's published surface, from a list of $M$ nodes to a single fingerprint scalar---$O(M)$ down to $O(1)$---which is a win the verifier feels but the glue's own gate count does not show, and which later sections collect. The second is a change in the glue's coverage check: where plain-sort's glue sorts all $n$ published node values and reads off $0$ through $n-1$, plain-product's glue folds them into a grand product instead. It is this second effect that the measurement is needed to pin down, because it is the easy one to overstate. The tempting summary is that the product makes coverage cheap by making it _small_---an $O(n)$ sort collapsed to an $O(K)$ handful of multiplications. That is not what happens, and @chap:hierarchical was careful to say so: the product glue still forms its target product over all $n$ values of ${0, dots, n-1}$, so its coverage is still $O(n)$, only of a cheaper kind. The gate counts settle which description is right, and it is the careful one.

The lever is a change of slope, not of class. Fit the glue against $n$ at a fixed four segments and both mechanisms come out linear in $n$: plain-sort's glue grows at about $19$ gates per node, plain-product's at about $2.8$---the same $O(n)$, a slope roughly seven times gentler. @fig:lever shows the two families of curves, the product's sitting well below the sort's and rising at a shallower angle, but rising: at every $K$ the product glue climbs with $n$ and never flattens into the constant an $O(K)$ coverage would give. The grand product touches all $n$ nodes exactly as the sort did. What the lever changed is not how many nodes the coverage visits but how much each visit costs.

That sevenfold gap is the witness inversion of @sec:witness-inversion, surfacing again at the recombiner. The sort's coverage is a dynamic, prover-steered permutation check---a read-only memory sorted and scanned---and every node it covers drags that machinery behind it, some nineteen gates' worth. The product's coverage is straight-line arithmetic, one multiplication per node into a running product, under three gates and no prover-chosen memory at all. Same length, different instrument: the lever does not shorten the coverage check, it cheapens every step of it, and cheapens the witness work behind each step by more still---the very inversion @sec:witness-inversion measured on the flat row, paying off a second time here at the glue.

There _is_ an $O(K)$ term in the glue, and naming it shows exactly what the convenient summary mistook. On top of the $O(n)$ coverage, every glue carries a cost that grows with the number of segments: the $K$ boundary edges joining one segment to the next, each proved against the committed root by its own Merkle path, for an $O(K dot D)$ contribution. Hold $n$ fixed and raise $K$ and the glue rises on that account alone---plain-product's from about $8.4$k gates at two segments to $18.8$k at eight. The summary that called the product glue "$O(K)$" had this term in hand and mistook the part for the whole; the coverage it left out is the larger contribution and the $O(n)$ one. The honest decomposition is a glue of three parts---an $O(n)$ coverage, an $O(K dot D)$ set of boundary edges, and a fixed remainder---with the lever acting on the slope of the first.

So the lever's worth is now exact. It does not lower the glue's complexity class; it cuts the coverage's per-node cost about sevenfold and strips the dynamic memory out of it, and---where the gate count cannot see---it shrinks each segment's published surface from $O(M)$ to $O(1)$, which is where the verifier-side savings of the sections ahead will come from. That cheaper glue is why plain-product carried the lighter tax of @sub:dualism-measured, and, once commitments enter, why committed-product's scalar re-fold dilutes where committed-sort's $O(n)$ re-fold will not. The lever is a constant-factor win where the gates can see it and a structural one where only the surface can; the figure that once summarised it as a change of order was reaching for the second saving and misnaming the first.

