With the two gate predictions read---the dualism confirmed, the lever sharpened---the per-variant picture of the prover's _work_ is complete: it is conserved, taxed by a glue whose coverage the lever cheapens but does not shrink. What none of it has shown is the thing decomposition was actually for. Total work was never the point; time was. Whether cutting the proof into pieces and proving them at once on separate machines clears the wall @sec:flat-eval ended on is the next question, and the first the chapter asks of the clock rather than the gate.

#section([Proving in Parallel], label: <sec:parallel-proving>)

The wall of @sec:flat-eval was a wall of memory, and behind it of time: one prover holding one enormous circuit, until the circuit no longer fit. Decomposition's promise was to retire that single prover for $K$ small ones running at once, each holding only a piece. The previous section showed the promise costs something---a conserved total and a glue tax on top---but said nothing about whether it is kept. That is a question for the clock, and the clock answers in two parts: how much sooner the proof finishes when the segments run in parallel, which this section reads first, and how much less memory each prover needs, which it reads second and which is what truly clears the wall.

One point about method governs every number that follows. We did not run $K$ provers at once on one machine; doing so would have them fight over the same cores and memory bandwidth, and would measure the contention rather than the construction. We measured each proof alone on the full machine and compose the times as the distributed model prescribes: $K$ segments proved at once on $K$ machines finish when the slowest of them does, and the glue, which needs them all, runs after. The critical path is therefore the slowest segment's prove time plus the glue's. This is the ideal-parallel wall-clock, a compute-only upper bound on what the construction would deliver across $K$ uncontended machines---not what a single shared machine would---and we report it as exactly that.

#subsection([The Speedup, and Its Ceiling], label: <sub:speedup>)

Read the speedup as the flat prove time over the critical path (@fig:speedup-memory, left). At $n = 3000$ cut into eight segments, the plain-product proof finishes in $13.5$ seconds against the flat proof's $86$, a $6.4$-fold speedup, with committed-product matching it at $6.5$. The win grows with $K$---roughly $1.9 times$ at two segments, $3.5$ at four, $6.4$ at eight---and grows slightly with $n$ as well, the segments coming to outweigh the fixed per-proof costs.

It is not, however, the eightfold that eight segments might seem to promise, and the shortfall has two sources, both already in hand. The first is the dualism. Eight segments sum to a little _more_ than the flat proof's work, not less, and each carries its own fixed per-proof overhead that does not shrink with the piece; so the slowest segment at $K = 8$ takes not an eighth of the flat time but nearer a seventh, capping the segment-bound speedup around $6.7 times$ before the glue is even added. The second source is the glue, and it is where the mechanism at last reaches the clock.

The glue runs last and alone, on the critical path, and how long it takes is the fingerprint lever's bill come due. For the product variants it is almost nothing---half a second at the tail of a thirteen-second path, the cheap straight-line coverage of @sub:lever-measured. For the sort variants it is the $O(n)$ coverage sort, and sitting on the critical path it is a _serial_ tail that parallelism cannot touch: about seven seconds for plain-sort at $n = 3000$, eleven for committed-sort with its extra re-fold. That tail is the entire difference. The sort and product segments finish in essentially the same time, near twelve and a half seconds; yet plain-sort's speedup falls to $4.7 times$ and committed-sort's to $3.8$, each made to wait out a serial glue the product variants simply do not have. The lever's seven-fold-cheaper coverage, an abstraction in the gate count of @sub:lever-measured, is here a concrete five-to-eleven-second wait, and Amdahl's law converts it directly into lost speedup. The left panel of @fig:speedup-memory shows the consequence: the product curves press toward the ideal line, the sort curves bend away beneath them, and committed-sort, carrying the heaviest glue, bends furthest.

#figure(
  image("/assets/figures/07_speedup_and_memory_vs_K.pdf", width: 100%),
  caption: [Parallel proving at $n = 3000$, against the flat baseline, versus segment count $K$. Left: speedup, the flat prove time over the critical path (slowest segment plus glue). Right: per-prover peak memory reduction. The product variants (squares) approach the ideal $K times$ in both; the sort variants (circles) are capped---by the glue's serial $O(n)$ coverage sort in time, by the glue's $O(n)$ footprint in memory---and committed-sort, with the heaviest glue, falls furthest in each. Isolated per-proof measurements composed as the distributed model prescribes (uncontended machines): a compute-only upper bound.],
